# Preact Best Practices

This document serves as a comprehensive guide for developers using Preact, outlining essential practices for code organization, performance, and component architecture. Follow these guidelines to enhance your Preact development experience.

## Code Organization and Structure

### Use a Modular File Structure
Organize your components in a modular way to improve maintainability and scalability. Each component should reside in its own directory.

```plaintext
src/
├── components/
│   ├── Button/
│   │   ├── Button.jsx
│   │   └── Button.css
│   ├── Header/
│   │   ├── Header.jsx
│   │   └── Header.css
│   └── Footer/
│       ├── Footer.jsx
│       └── Footer.css
└── App.jsx
```

### Naming Conventions
Use PascalCase for component names and camelCase for props. This enhances readability and consistency.

```javascript
// ✅ GOOD
const MyComponent = ({ myProp }) => {
    return <div>{myProp}</div>;
};

// ❌ BAD
const mycomponent = ({ My_Prop }) => {
    return <div>{My_Prop}</div>;
};
```

## Common Patterns and Anti-patterns

### Prefer Functional Components with Hooks
Always use functional components with hooks for state and lifecycle management. This is the modern approach and leads to cleaner code.

```javascript
// ✅ GOOD
import { useState } from 'preact/hooks';

const Counter = () => {
    const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
    return <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>{count}</button>;
};

// ❌ BAD
class Counter extends Component {
    state = { count: 0 };

    render() {
        return <button onClick={() => this.setState({ count: this.state.count + 1 })}>{this.state.count}</button>;
    }
}
```

## Performance Considerations

### Use Signals for State Management
Leverage Preact's Signals for high-performance state management. This avoids Virtual DOM overhead by updating specific nodes directly.

```javascript
import { signal } from '@preact/signals';

const count = signal(0);

const Counter = () => {
    return <button onClick={() => count.value++}>{count.value}</button>;
};
```

### Avoid Unnecessary Re-renders
Use `memo` to prevent re-renders of components that don't depend on changing props.

```javascript
import { memo } from 'preact/compat';

const ExpensiveComponent = memo(({ data }) => {
    // expensive calculations
    return <div>{data}</div>;
});
```

## Common Pitfalls and Gotchas

### Beware of Hydration Mismatches
Ensure that the server and client outputs are consistent to prevent hydration issues. Always render the same content on both server and client.

```javascript
// ✅ GOOD
const App = () => {
    return <div>{process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production' ? 'Production' : 'Development'}</div>;
};

// ❌ BAD
const App = () => {
    return <div>{Math.random()}</div>; // This will differ between server and client
};
```

## Component Architecture

### Use Composition Over Inheritance
Favor component composition to create flexible and reusable components.

```javascript
const Button = ({ children, onClick }) => (
    <button onClick={onClick}>{children}</button>
);

const App = () => (
    <Button onClick={() => alert('Clicked!')}>Click Me</Button>
);
```

## State Management

### Use Context for Global State
When managing global state, use Preact's Context API for better performance and clarity.

```javascript
import { createContext, useContext, useState } from 'preact/hooks';

const AppContext = createContext();

const AppProvider = ({ children }) => {
    const [state, setState] = useState({ user: null });
    return (
        <AppContext.Provider value={[state, setState]}>
            {children}
        </AppContext.Provider>
    );
};

const useAppContext = () => useContext(AppContext);
```

## Accessibility

### Ensure All Interactive Elements Are Keyboard Accessible
Make sure all buttons and interactive elements are keyboard accessible and provide meaningful labels.

```javascript
// ✅ GOOD
<button aria-label="Close" onClick={handleClose}>X</button>

// ❌ BAD
<button onClick={handleClose}>X</button> // No context for screen readers
```

## Hooks Best Practices

### Use Custom Hooks for Reusable Logic
Encapsulate reusable logic in custom hooks to keep components clean and focused.

```javascript
import { useEffect, useState } from 'preact/hooks';

const useFetchData = (url) => {
    const [data, setData] = useState(null);
    useEffect(() => {
        fetch(url)
            .then(response => response.json())
            .then(setData);
    }, [url]);
    return data;
};

const DataComponent = () => {
    const data = useFetchData('/api/data');
    return <div>{data ? JSON.stringify(data) : 'Loading...'}</div>;
};
```

By following these best practices, you will ensure a robust, maintainable, and high-performance Preact application. Always prioritize modern patterns and keep your code organized for the best developer experience.